### Attach XDP Programs to Network Interfaces

Source: https://context7.com/cilium/ebpf/llms.txt

Shows how to attach an XDP program to a specific network interface for high-performance packet processing. It covers interface lookup, program attachment with specific flags, and monitoring packet counts via eBPF maps.

```go
package main

import (
    "log"
    "net"
    "os"
    "os/signal"
    "time"

    "github.com/cilium/ebpf/link"
    "github.com/cilium/ebpf/rlimit"
)

//go:generate go tool bpf2go -target amd64 xdp xdp.c

func main() {
    if err := rlimit.RemoveMemlock(); err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    var objs xdpObjects
    if err := loadXdpObjects(&objs, nil); err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("loading objects: %v", err)
    }
    defer objs.Close()

    // Get interface by name
    iface, err := net.InterfaceByName("eth0")
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("getting interface: %v", err)
    }

    // Attach XDP program to interface
    xdpLink, err := link.AttachXDP(link.XDPOptions{
        Program:   objs.XdpProg,
        Interface: iface.Index,
        Flags:     link.XDPGenericMode, // Use XDPDriverMode for native mode
    })
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("attaching XDP: %v", err)
    }
    defer xdpLink.Close()

    log.Printf("XDP program attached to %s", iface.Name)

    // Read packet counts
    stop := make(chan os.Signal, 1)
    signal.Notify(stop, os.Interrupt)

    ticker := time.NewTicker(time.Second)
    defer ticker.Stop()

    for {
        select {
        case <-ticker.C:
            var count uint64
            if err := objs.PktCount.Lookup(uint32(0), &count); err != nil {
                log.Printf("map lookup: %v", err)
                continue
            }
            log.Printf("Packets: %d", count)
        case <-stop:
            return
        }
    }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Read events from eBPF using Ring Buffers

Source: https://context7.com/cilium/ebpf/llms.txt

Demonstrates how to initialize a ring buffer reader to consume events from an eBPF map. This approach is preferred for lower overhead compared to perf event arrays.

```Go
package main

import (
	"bytes"
	"encoding/binary"
	"errors"
	"log"
	"os"
	"os/signal"

	"github.com/cilium/ebpf/link"
	"github.com/cilium/ebpf/ringbuf"
	"github.com/cilium/ebpf/rlimit"
)

//go:generate go tool bpf2go -target amd64 ringbuf ringbuffer.c

type Event struct {
	Pid  uint32
	Comm [16]byte
}

func main() {
	if err := rlimit.RemoveMemlock(); err != nil {
		log.Fatal(err)
	}

	var objs ringbufObjects
	if err := loadRingbufObjects(&objs, nil); err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("loading objects: %v", err)
	}
	defer objs.Close()

	kp, err := link.Kprobe("sys_execve", objs.KprobeExecve, nil)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("attaching kprobe: %v", err)
	}
	defer kp.Close()

	rd, err := ringbuf.NewReader(objs.Events)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("creating ringbuf reader: %v", err)
	}
	defer rd.Close()

	stop := make(chan os.Signal, 1)
	signal.Notify(stop, os.Interrupt)

	go func() {
		<-stop
		rd.Close()
	}()

	log.Println("Waiting for events...")

	var event Event
	for {
		record, err := rd.Read()
		if err != nil {
			if errors.Is(err, ringbuf.ErrClosed) {
				log.Println("Ring buffer closed, exiting")
				return
			}
			log.Printf("reading from ringbuf: %v", err)
			continue
		}

		if err := binary.Read(bytes.NewBuffer(record.RawSample), binary.LittleEndian, &event); err != nil {
			log.Printf("parsing event: %v", err)
			continue
		}

		comm := string(bytes.TrimRight(event.Comm[:], "\x00"))
		log.Printf("PID: %d, Command: %s", event.Pid, comm)
	}
}
```

--------------------------------

### Attach Kprobes and Kretprobes using Go

Source: https://context7.com/cilium/ebpf/llms.txt

Demonstrates attaching eBPF programs to kernel function entry and return points using the cilium/ebpf link package. It includes memory limit configuration, object loading, and periodic map lookups to monitor function calls.

```go
package main

import (
    "log"
    "time"

    "github.com/cilium/ebpf/link"
    "github.com/cilium/ebpf/rlimit"
)

//go:generate go tool bpf2go -target amd64 kprobe kprobe.c

func main() {
    if err := rlimit.RemoveMemlock(); err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    var objs kprobeObjects
    if err := loadKprobeObjects(&objs, nil); err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("loading objects: %v", err)
    }
    defer objs.Close()

    // Attach kprobe to sys_execve (program entry)
    kp, err := link.Kprobe("sys_execve", objs.KprobeExecve, nil)
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("attaching kprobe: %v", err)
    }
    defer kp.Close()

    // Attach kretprobe (function return)
    kret, err := link.Kretprobe("sys_execve", objs.KretprobeExecve, &link.KprobeOptions{
        Cookie: 0x1234, // Arbitrary value accessible via bpf_get_attach_cookie()
    })
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatalf("attaching kretprobe: %v", err)
    }
    defer kret.Close()

    // Read from map periodically
    ticker := time.NewTicker(time.Second)
    defer ticker.Stop()

    for range ticker.C {
        var count uint64
        if err := objs.CountMap.Lookup(uint32(0), &count); err != nil {
            log.Fatalf("reading map: %v", err)
        }
        log.Printf("sys_execve called %d times", count)
    }
}
```

### eBPF Go

Source: https://context7.com/cilium/ebpf/llms.txt

eBPF Go (ebpf-go) is a pure Go library that provides a comprehensive toolkit for interacting with eBPF programs from Go applications. It enables developers to load eBPF bytecode into the kernel, manage data exchange via eBPF maps, and attach programs to various kernel hooks such as kprobes, tracepoints, and XDP. Designed with minimal external dependencies, the library is well-suited for long-running processes and includes specialized packages for assembling instructions, reading BTF information, and handling perf event arrays or ring buffers.

--------------------------------

### Resource Limits

Source: https://github.com/cilium/ebpf/blob/main/docs/ebpf/concepts/rlimit.md

Creating eBPF objects like Maps, Programs, and BTF blobs requires kernel memory allocation. Historically, before kernel version 5.11, the memory available for these allocations was governed by the `RLIMIT_MEMLOCK` rlimit value, which could be checked using `ulimit -l`. However, starting with kernel version 5.11, the Linux kernel transitioned to using memory cgroups (memcg) for managing memory limits related to eBPF objects. In this new model, eBPF allocations are accounted for within the cgroup's memory limits, similar to other process memory usage. These limits can be monitored and adjusted via cgroupfs, the standard interface for container memory controls.

